4 lifeguard for each one hundred (100) or more bathers.
5 (4) At a pool where the use is intended for aquatic events, swimming practice, or
6 swimming competition, the swimming coach or instructor that provides instruction
7 during the program may count as a lifeguard, provided the coach or instructor can
8 supervise the entire group.
9 (5) Notwithstanding subsections (2) and (3) of this section, the Cabinet for Health and
10 Family Services may allow Class A and Class B pools to submit an alternative
11 lifeguard staffing plan that has been certified by a third-party compliance specialist
12 that is recognized by the Cabinet for Health and Family Services.
13 (6) All Class A and Class B pools shall be equipped with an emergency shut-off switch
14 to disconnect power to pool recirculation, chemical feed, and electrical devices
15 engaged with the water circulation system, which is located at a place quickly
16 accessible to lifeguards and other pool staff, but secure from the public.
17 (7) Any pool located on the same plat as a single-family residence intended only for
18 the use of the owner and his or her guests, regardless of whether the guests
19 gained use of the private single-family residence pool through a sharing platform
20 or pay a fee for its use,[and not used in connection with a home occupation or
21 business] shall be exempted from the provisions of this section.
22 (8) The Cabinet for Health and Family Services shall promulgate administrative
23 regulations in accordance with KRS Chapter 13A to implement this section.
